24":"1224","1212":"1212","about 1229":"circa 1229","1289":"1289","1232":"1232","1210":"1210","1320":"1320","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sefton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Sefton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sefton, Merseyside, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Sefton, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Sefton, Lancashire, England":"Sefton, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1212–1250":"1212–1250","1210–1289":"1210–1289","1232–1320":"1232–1320","1237–1294":"1237–1294","1239–Male":"1239–Deceased","1186–1250":"1186–1250","1190–1263":"1190–1263","1190":"1190","1263":"1263","1186":"1186","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","1239":"1239","1237":"1237","1215":"1215","about 1239":"about 1239","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","about 1229":"about 1229","1289":"1289","1232":"1232","1210":"1210","1320":"1320","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Sefton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Sefton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Sefton, Merseyside, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Sefton, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Sefton, Lancashire, England":"Sefton, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thorne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly southern): variant of   Thorn   1.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’. Compare   Thornton  .","Swedish (mainly <b>Thörne</b>): ornamental or perhaps topographic name from <i>törne</i> ‘rose bush’ or <i>thorn</i>, an ornamental spelling of <i>torn</i> ‘thorn bush’."],"variants":[{"name":"Thorn","meanings":["English and Danish: topographic name for someone who lived by a thorn bush or hedge (Old English, Old Norse <i>thorn</i>, Middle English <i>thorn(e)</i>, <i>torn(e)</i>). The name is also found in Sweden.","English: habitational name from a place called with Old English, Old Norse <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn bush’ (see 1 above), for example Thorne in Kent, Somerset, and South Yorkshire.","North German and Danish: topographic name for someone who lived near a tower, from Middle Low German <i>torn</i> ‘tower’."]},{"name":"Thurn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Katharina, Milbert.","German: topographic name for someone who lived near a watchtower, or a metonymic occupational name for someone responsible for manning one, from Middle High German <i>turn</i>, <i>turm</i> ‘tower’. In some cases it may be a habitational name from any of the many places called with this word in the Rhineland, Bavaria, Austria, and Bohemia.","English (Warwickshire): variant of   Thorne  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":3,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":12,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Thorne was born in 1212, in Lancashire, England, her father, Sir Allan Thorne, was 26 and her mother, Alicia Bickerstaffe, was 23. She married Sir William Molyneux Lord of Sefton about 1229, in Sefton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1250, in Sefton, Lancashire, England, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1212–1250":"1212–1250","1210–1289":"1210–1289","1232–1320":"1232–1320","1237–1294":"1237–1294","1239–Male":"1239–Surnud","1186–1250":"1186–1250","1190–1263":"1190–1263","1190":"1190","1263":"1263","1186":"1186","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","1239":"1239","1237":"1237","1215":"1215","about 1239":"umbes 1239","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","about 1229":"umbes 1229","1289":"1289","1232":"1232","1210":"1210","1320":"1320","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sefton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Sefton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sefton, Merseyside, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"